00:11:54,270 --> 00:11:59,960
And this has kept all sorts of
people happy doing experiments

253
00:11:59,960 --> 00:12:03,320
where they do mixes and
matches of starting with 100

254
00:12:03,320 --> 00:12:06,870
different pictures of people
and combine subsets of them

255
00:12:06,870 --> 00:12:09,420
and having people rating
attractiveness and stuff.

256
00:12:09,420 --> 00:12:12,360
And it's this absolutely
bizarre thing--

257
00:12:12,360 --> 00:12:15,490
that the more faces that go
into a composite, the more,

258
00:12:15,490 --> 00:12:18,760
on the average, people perceive
them as being attractive,

259
00:12:18,760 --> 00:12:21,700
amid incredibly
subtle differences

260
00:12:21,700 --> 00:12:25,910
between a composite picture
of 50 faces versus 25,

261
00:12:25,910 --> 00:12:29,760
all of that, people are able to
pick up the differences-- not

262
00:12:29,760 --> 00:12:31,490
necessarily consciously.

263
00:12:31,490 --> 00:12:33,530
So what is that about?

264
00:12:33,530 --> 00:12:38,254
And what became clear,
many decades later,

265
00:12:38,254 --> 00:12:39,670
is that what happens
when you make

266
00:12:39,670 --> 00:12:42,340
a lot of faces all
into one composite

267
00:12:42,340 --> 00:12:46,350
is you get a highly
symmetrical face.

268
00:12:46,350 --> 00:12:49,810
And this seems to be the
key thing that comes through

269
00:12:49,810 --> 00:12:51,720
in that realm of attractiveness.

270
00:12:51,720 --> 00:12:55,580
Which is that, when you average
in a whole lot of faces,

271
00:12:55,580 --> 00:12:59,330
one of the things you average
is the averageness of the face.

272
00:12:59,330 --> 00:13:01,250
And you get rid of asymmetries.

273
00:13:01,250 --> 00:13:06,620
And everyone knows that-- who
would you want to mate with?

274
00:13:06,620 --> 00:13:07,120
[LAUGHTER]

275
00:13:07,120 --> 00:13:10,460
OK, so, thereby
proving the point.

276
00:13:10,460 --> 00:13:14,500
And what you've got is,
symmetry is apparently

277
00:13:14,500 --> 00:13:16,720
a good, reliable
marker of health.

278
00:13:16,720 --> 00:13:20,070
Wildly asymmetric
faces are typically

279
00:13:20,070 --> 00:13:23,820
the result of complications--
developmental ones-- health

280
00:13:23,820 --> 00:13:24,780
sort of issues.

281
00:13:24,780 --> 00:13:28,630
So the general interpretation
is that symmetry is attractive

282
00:13:28,630 --> 00:13:31,790
because it is a
marker of health.

283
00:13:31,790 --> 00:13:34,760
And every single
article you will ever

284
00:13:34,760 --> 00:13:36,987
read in sort of the
lay press-- or even

285
00:13:36,987 --> 00:13:38,570
in some of the science
journals, which

286
00:13:38,570 --> 00:13:40,070
should be above
this sort of thing--

287
00:13:40,070 --> 00:13:43,580
will have the picture of some
famously attractive somebody

288
00:13:43,580 --> 00:13:45,340
or other, with
the face up there,

289
00:13:45,340 --> 00:13:47,950
and all the little caliper
markings, and showing

290
00:13:47,950 --> 00:13:51,760
the same sizes, and then
some poor schnook who's

291
00:13:51,760 --> 00:13:56,170
chosen to be the asymmetric
face who's stuck up there.

292
00:13:56,170 --> 00:14:00,420
Did the Newsweek article wind
up being in the readings?

293
00:14:00,420 --> 00:14:02,380
No, it wasn't-- yes.

294
00:14:02,380 --> 00:14:03,530
OK.

295
00:14:03,530 --> 00:14:05,670
Lyle Lovett-- is that
the face they had there

296
00:14:05,670 --> 00:14:08,630
that they were making vicious
fun of and pointing out

297
00:14:08,630 --> 00:14:10,540
lip asymmetries and such?

298
00:14:10,540 --> 00:14:15,730
Something about the symmetry
seems to be a marker for health

299
00:14:15,730 --> 00:14:17,390
and is considered
more attractive.

300
00:14:17,390 --> 00:14:20,720
And people can pick up
astonishingly subtle

301
00:14:20,720 --> 00:14:22,620
asymmetries in faces.

302
00:14:22,620 --> 00:14:26,240
Babies, at two
months of age, show--

303
00:14:26,240 --> 00:14:28,680
when you are doing
morphed faces,

304
00:14:28,680 --> 00:14:33,350
composite faces, where you
can very minorly adjust

305
00:14:33,350 --> 00:14:36,750
the degree of symmetry or
asymmetry in the face-- babies,

306
00:14:36,750 --> 00:14:39,030
at two months of
age, are already

307
00:14:39,030 --> 00:14:43,500
preferring to look at pictures
of more symmetrical faces.

308
00:14:43,500 --> 00:14:46,730
You find this in lots of
other species, as well.

309
00:14:46,730 --> 00:14:50,040
When you look at
animals lever-pressing--

310
00:14:50,040 --> 00:14:51,830
rats, for example,
getting access

311
00:14:51,830 --> 00:14:54,530
to other rats of
the opposite gender.

312
00:14:54,530 --> 00:14:57,380
And you will see there's
a bias for symmetry there.

313
00:14:57,380 --> 00:14:59,470
There is a bias in
nonhuman primates

314
00:14:59,470 --> 00:15:01,290
for more symmetrical faces.

315
00:15:01,290 --> 00:15:03,480
How's this for a
nutty study that

316
00:15:03,480 --> 00:15:07,380
was published about five
years ago, in Nature?

317
00:15:07,380 --> 00:15:11,290
And this one reported that
people who had symmetrical

318
00:15:11,290 --> 00:15:15,200
faces were better dancers.

319
00:15:15,200 --> 00:15:17,450
OK, let's work through that one.

320
00:15:17,450 --> 00:15:19,090
What was that one about?

321
00:15:19,090 --> 00:15:23,090
And they did-- it
was a bizarre study,

322
00:15:23,090 --> 00:15:26,050
but somehow, nonetheless,
it was irresistible.

323
00:15:26,050 --> 00:15:27,070
Here's what they showed.

324
00:15:27,070 --> 00:15:30,030
They filmed all sorts
of people dancing.

325
00:15:30,030 --> 00:15:32,380
And, no doubt, they
did perfect controls

326
00:15:32,380 --> 00:15:34,540
and they, like,
made sure everybody

327
00:15:34,540 --> 00:15:36,570
danced to the same
thing, which was,

328
00:15:36,570 --> 00:15:40,660
like-- oh, I don't
know-- something--

329
00:15:40,660 --> 00:15:43,390
a scientist rapping
to something or other.

330
00:15:43,390 --> 00:15:45,090
And people dancing away, there.

331
00:15:45,090 --> 00:15:47,729
And then they used
this amazing technique,

332
00:15:47,729 --> 00:15:49,520
which I didn't understand
in the slightest,

333
00:15:49,520 --> 00:15:52,960
with some sort of
camera-capture technique

334
00:15:52,960 --> 00:15:55,780
that would make everybody
dancing look like Gumby.

335
00:15:55,780 --> 00:15:59,080
So you took out all the
individual features-- anything

336
00:15:59,080 --> 00:15:59,600
at all.

337
00:15:59,600 --> 00:16:01,600
And people would then
rate them on the dancing.

338
00:16:01,600 --> 00:16:03,350
And it would turn
out that people

339
00:16:03,350 --> 00:16:06,320
who were rated by both
genders, of either gender,

340
00:16:06,320 --> 00:16:08,630
as being a better
dancer, when you then

341
00:16:08,630 --> 00:16:10,860
went and checked out
their faces afterward,

342
00:16:10,860 --> 00:16:14,950
with your slide rule, turned out
to have more symmetrical faces.

343
00:16:14,950 --> 00:16:15,790
Whoa!

344
00:16:15,790 --> 00:16:17,260
Isn't that bizarre?

345
00:16:17,260 --> 00:16:21,020
My guess would be that this is
one of those indirect routes

346
00:16:21,020 --> 00:16:23,210
that we've already
seen some examples of.

347
00:16:23,210 --> 00:16:26,270
My guess would be,
more symmetrical faces

348
00:16:26,270 --> 00:16:29,660
are thus more attractive,
and thus such people

349
00:16:29,660 --> 00:16:33,090
are treated better and
are more confident in life

350
00:16:33,090 --> 00:16:36,142
and more extroverted and
more comfortable dancing

351
00:16:36,142 --> 00:16:37,600
when they knew that
they were going

352
00:16:37,600 --> 00:16:39,230
to wind up looking like Gumby.

353
00:16:39,230 --> 00:16:42,520
So that is probably what
the indirect route is.

354
00:16:42,520 --> 00:16:46,630
But running through all of
this is this symmetry business.

355
00:16:46,630 --> 00:16:48,940
And it's there in
species after species.

356
00:16:48,940 --> 00:16:53,210
And humans are amazing at
picking up subtleties at it.

357
00:16:53,210 --> 00:16:57,360
One additional finding in
the symmetry world-- women

358
00:16:57,360 --> 00:17:00,100
at the time that
they are ovulating

359
00:17:00,100 --> 00:17:05,246
have their faces become ever
so slightly more symmetrical.

360
00:17:05,246 --> 00:17:06,329
[COMMENTS AMONG  STUDENTS]

361
00:17:06,329 --> 00:17:09,310
OK, well, that's
going to get people

362
00:17:09,310 --> 00:17:12,270
all nutsy in the
coming weeks, no doubt,

363
00:17:12,270 --> 00:17:14,400
trying to figure out
what that's about.

364
00:17:14,400 --> 00:17:17,040
I did not see a good explanation
as to what that was about,

365
00:17:17,040 --> 00:17:19,770
but that has been observed
in the literature.

366
00:17:19,770 --> 00:17:21,920
So the first thing,
in terms of what

367
00:17:21,920 --> 00:17:23,960
one looks for in
a mate, if you're

368
00:17:23,960 --> 00:17:28,170
some basic social animal-- first
set of features, this business

369
00:17:28,170 --> 00:17:29,890
about symmetry.

370
00:17:29,890 --> 00:17:33,430
Next realm-- this whole
world of secondary sexual

371
00:17:33,430 --> 00:17:34,960
characteristics.

372
00:17:34,960 --> 00:17:39,800
Why is it that female
peacocks like male peacocks

373
00:17:39,800 --> 00:17:42,620
to look like male peacocks,
and all that sort of thing?

374
00:17:42,620 --> 00:17:44,180
What is that about?

375
00:17:44,180 --> 00:17:46,980
And people have been working
with this one for years.

376
00:17:46,980 --> 00:17:49,520
And there is a
zoologist named Zahavi

377
00:17:49,520 --> 00:17:52,270
who has been very influential--
Israeli zoologist--

378
00:17:52,270 --> 00:17:55,700
who came up with what is called
the "handicap principle."

379
00:17:55,700 --> 00:17:56,700
As follows.

380
00:17:56,700 --> 00:18:01,400
Why is it that secondary sexual
characteristics are appealing?

381
00:18:01,400 --> 00:18:05,450
Characteristics that exaggerate
the difference in appearance

382
00:18:05,450 --> 00:18:06,470
by gender.

383
00:18:06,470 --> 00:18:07,500
Why is that appealing?

384
00:18:07,500 --> 00:18:11,570
Because, in effect, the bigger
and more garish and the more

385
00:18:11,570 --> 00:18:14,700
over-the-top your secondary
sexual characteristic is,

386
00:18:14,700 --> 00:18:17,050
the more you were
communicating to the world,

387
00:18:17,050 --> 00:18:21,610
I have so much energy on
board, and I am so healthy,

388
00:18:21,610 --> 00:18:25,090
that I can afford to squander
massive numbers of calories

389
00:18:25,090 --> 00:18:28,410
on these asinine neon antlers
I'm walking around with.

390
00:18:28,410 --> 00:18:30,530
That it's an argument
there that this

391
00:18:30,530 --> 00:18:34,780
is a display of, in a sense,
conspicuous consumption--

392
00:18:34,780 --> 00:18:39,110
the ability to put energy into
these large secondary sexual

393
00:18:39,110 --> 00:18:39,990
characteristics.

394
00:18:39,990 --> 00:18:44,940
That these are markers of health
and of good immune systems.

395
00:18:44,940 --> 00:18:46,790
Lots of evidence for this.

396
00:18:46,790 --> 00:18:50,170
And this is, by now, a whole
field that people have studied.

397
00:18:50,170 --> 00:18:51,690
One version of it.

398
00:18:51,690 --> 00:18:55,151
These were studies done
with marsupial mice.

399
00:18:55,151 --> 00:18:56,650
And there was
something having to do

400
00:18:56,650 --> 00:18:59,280
with their marsupialesque
reproduction that

401
00:18:59,280 --> 00:19:01,770
made this the species
to do this with.

402
00:19:01,770 --> 00:19:06,760
But it was doing sperm
insemination of females.

403
00:19:06,760 --> 00:19:10,150
And what was done was
that they took the sperm

404
00:19:10,150 --> 00:19:13,850
from these male marsupial
mice, after measuring

405
00:19:13,850 --> 00:19:16,680
some secondary sexual
characteristics in them.

406
00:19:16,680 --> 00:19:18,550
I believe that they
don't have antlers,

407
00:19:18,550 --> 00:19:20,740
but I don't remember what
the actual thing was.

408
00:19:20,740 --> 00:19:22,520
And what they were
able to do was

409
00:19:22,520 --> 00:19:25,410
to now have sperm from
males of differing

410
00:19:25,410 --> 00:19:29,340
degrees of exaggerated
secondary characteristics.

411
00:19:29,340 --> 00:19:32,410
And what they showed
was that the males who

412
00:19:32,410 --> 00:19:36,190
had the more dramatic secondary
characteristics-- their sperm

413
00:19:36,190 --> 00:19:38,050
were more fertile.

414
00:19:38,050 --> 00:19:42,030
So that was a first big vote
in this handicap principle

415
00:19:42,030 --> 00:19:45,810
that things like
secondary appearances,

416
00:19:45,810 --> 00:19:51,220
secondary sexual ones,
can be a marker for health

417
00:19:51,220 --> 00:19:53,320
and/or fertility.

418
00:19:53,320 --> 00:19:54,900
Now why should that be?

419
00:19:54,900 --> 00:19:58,870
What you essentially are seeing
there is, it is a display.

420
00:19:58,870 --> 00:20:00,390
It is a potlatch.

421
00:20:00,390 --> 00:20:02,430
It is a display
of how much energy

422
00:20:02,430 --> 00:20:05,650
you can afford to waste
and thus how much you

423
00:20:05,650 --> 00:20:07,020
must have on board.

424
00:20:07,020 --> 00:20:10,650
It is a marker of health
and good immunity.

425
00:20:10,650 --> 00:20:13,250
This has been shown
in lots of studies.

426
00:20:13,250 --> 00:20:16,190
Along the lines
of, the same sort

427
00:20:16,190 --> 00:20:20,830
of signals that give rise to the
secondary sexual characteristic

428
00:20:20,830 --> 00:20:23,460
are markers of immune function.

429
00:20:23,460 --> 00:20:26,050
A well-functioning
immune system will

430
00:20:26,050 --> 00:20:29,150
be generating some
molecule which

431
00:20:29,150 --> 00:20:31,480
exaggerates facial coloration.

432
00:20:31,480 --> 00:20:33,676
And that's the secondary
sexual characteristic--

433
00:20:33,676 --> 00:20:38,630
that there is an explicit
link between immune function,

434
00:20:38,630 --> 00:20:42,350
immune competence,
and these markers.

435
00:20:42,350 --> 00:20:43,230
Interesting.

436
00:20:43,230 --> 00:20:45,240
A study that just
came out recently,

437
00:20:45,240 --> 00:20:48,660
looking at women from,
I believe it was,

438
00:20:48,660 --> 00:20:51,390
about 20 different
industrialized countries.

439
00:20:51,390 --> 00:20:55,250
And what was shown was
that, in general, women

440
00:20:55,250 --> 00:20:57,300
have a preference
for faces of men

441
00:20:57,300 --> 00:21:00,040
that have strong pronounced
secondary characteristics--

442
00:21:00,040 --> 00:21:03,110
which is, big, jutting
jaw, high forehead,

443
00:21:03,110 --> 00:21:05,160
lots of muscle stuff going on.

444
00:21:05,160 --> 00:21:09,380
And what they showed was that
the longer the life expectancy

445
00:21:09,380 --> 00:21:12,480
in the particular country,
the better the economy,

446
00:21:12,480 --> 00:21:16,150
the better the quality of life,
the less women in that country

447
00:21:16,150 --> 00:21:19,710
had a bias towards
male-looking males.

448
00:21:19,710 --> 00:21:21,950
Which is extremely interesting.

449
00:21:21,950 --> 00:21:23,420
What's the comparison there?

450
00:21:23,420 --> 00:21:26,930
It was all those, like,
Scandinavian countries.

451
00:21:26,930 --> 00:21:28,740
Thank god for the
Scandinavian countries,

452
00:21:28,740 --> 00:21:32,370
because they always provide the
extreme of these distributions.

453
00:21:32,370 --> 00:21:34,250
So, in those
Scandinavian countries,

454
00:21:34,250 --> 00:21:36,920
like, there has not
been a guy who's been,

455
00:21:36,920 --> 00:21:38,970
like, selected for a date
because of the height

456
00:21:38,970 --> 00:21:41,710
of his forehead, in centuries.

457
00:21:41,710 --> 00:21:45,380
Whereas what they showed was,
in a lot of other cultures--

458
00:21:45,380 --> 00:21:48,360
which were the ones who were
most extreme on the list,

459
00:21:48,360 --> 00:21:50,720
I am not remembering,
which is not very helpful.

460
00:21:50,720 --> 00:21:52,900
But a very different
sort of end of things.

461
00:21:52,900 --> 00:21:56,040
And there, much stronger
selection for what

462
00:21:56,040 --> 00:22:00,950
are viewed as traits, as
markers of fecundity and health.

463
00:22:00,950 --> 00:22:02,760
More evidence about this.

464
00:22:02,760 --> 00:22:08,910
What you see is, all of this
is a signal-- all of this

465
00:22:08,910 --> 00:22:14,740
is a signal, not only in terms
of who you want to mate with,

466
00:22:14,740 --> 00:22:18,310
in terms of who you are
passing on your copies of genes

467
00:22:18,310 --> 00:22:21,890
in cooperation with,
but also the possibility

468
00:22:21,890 --> 00:22:25,030
that the other individual
is infectious with something

469
00:22:25,030 --> 00:22:25,740
or other.

470
00:22:25,740 --> 00:22:28,960
And throughout the
world of social beasts,

471
00:22:28,960 --> 00:22:32,430
nobody likes getting sexually
transmitted diseases.

472
00:22:32,430 --> 00:22:35,860
And a lot of what this whole
handicap principle is about,

473
00:22:35,860 --> 00:22:39,530
a lot of this advertising about
what a great immune system you

474
00:22:39,530 --> 00:22:42,470
have, is a way of
advertising, I do not

475
00:22:42,470 --> 00:22:44,690
have a communicable disease.

476
00:22:44,690 --> 00:22:47,330
All sorts of
species-- individuals

477
00:22:47,330 --> 00:22:50,820
are extremely good at
detecting the smells

478
00:22:50,820 --> 00:22:54,040
in the others of
parasitic infections,

479
00:22:54,040 --> 00:22:56,300
of all sorts of
other infections,

480
00:22:56,300 --> 00:22:58,890
and avoiding them
like the plague.

481
00:22:58,890 --> 00:23:01,810
A common theme in lots
and lots of species.

482
00:23:01,810 --> 00:23:05,560
Rodents, where it's been most
studied-- a remarkable ability

483
00:23:05,560 --> 00:23:08,300
to smell out the health
of another individual.

484
00:23:08,300 --> 00:23:11,540
And this is someone you want to
stay away from-- that they're

485
00:23:11,540 --> 00:23:13,370
going to give you an STD.

486
00:23:13,370 --> 00:23:16,280
So that's part of it, as well.

487
00:23:16,280 --> 00:23:18,330
So, of course, what
you start getting

488
00:23:18,330 --> 00:23:21,660
are individuals trying
to cheat at all of this.

489
00:23:21,660 --> 00:23:25,070
And this is suddenly
the world of selection

490
00:23:25,070 --> 00:23:29,240
to uncouple your secondary
sexual characteristics

491
00:23:29,240 --> 00:23:30,640
from your health.

492
00:23:30,640 --> 00:23:32,680
Is there a way to cheat?

493
00:23:32,680 --> 00:23:33,530
Is there a way?

494
00:23:33,530 --> 00:23:36,590
And what is seen in
some bird species is,

495
00:23:36,590 --> 00:23:39,290
you've got some guy on
his deathbed, there.

496
00:23:39,290 --> 00:23:42,890
And what's he doing with
his last 3 and 1/2 calories

497
00:23:42,890 --> 00:23:44,000
worth of energy?

498
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:47,000
He's expending it
on wing coloration

499
00:23:47,000 --> 00:23:49,940
or whatever the secondary
characteristic thing is, there,

500
00:23:49,940 --> 00:23:52,220
that he's got four
