1239
00:57:18,850 --> 00:57:21,010
And what we're going to
be wrestling with, over

1240
00:57:21,010 --> 00:57:23,880
and over and over, in the
subject, as we march back,

1241
00:57:23,880 --> 00:57:28,770
here, is this whole issue of,
very little about the biology

1242
00:57:28,770 --> 00:57:31,900
of violence,
competition, all of that,

1243
00:57:31,900 --> 00:57:34,620
is about how to
do the behaviors.

1244
00:57:34,620 --> 00:57:37,560
It is all about
appropriate context.

1245
00:57:37,560 --> 00:57:39,340
And what we will
see is, all sorts

1246
00:57:39,340 --> 00:57:41,950
of realms of neurological
diseases, where things

1247
00:57:41,950 --> 00:57:46,820
go majorly wrong, in terms
of control against violence--

1248
00:57:46,820 --> 00:57:50,570
very rarely will it be that it's
the magnitude of violence which

1249
00:57:50,570 --> 00:57:51,300
is wrong.

1250
00:57:51,300 --> 00:57:53,920
What you see is, it's
in the wrong context.

1251
00:57:53,920 --> 00:57:56,500
Because if it's done
right we love it,

1252
00:57:56,500 --> 00:57:58,870
and we elect people who
have been good at it,

1253
00:57:58,870 --> 00:58:02,280
and we differentially mate with
them, and we pay to see it.

1254
00:58:02,280 --> 00:58:04,270
It's got to be in
the right setting.

1255
00:58:04,270 --> 00:58:07,510
There are very few of us who
viscerally are truly, truly

1256
00:58:07,510 --> 00:58:10,100
pacifists, all across the board.

1257
00:58:10,100 --> 00:58:13,570
We just don't like violence
in certain settings.

1258
00:58:13,570 --> 00:58:15,240
So that will be part
of the challenge,

1259
00:58:15,240 --> 00:58:18,930
here-- making sense of the
biology of social context.

1260
00:58:18,930 --> 00:58:20,410
And we've already
gotten some hints

1261
00:58:20,410 --> 00:58:23,140
about that in the last topic.

1262
00:58:23,140 --> 00:58:26,270
So, of course, what we
have to start off with

1263
00:58:26,270 --> 00:58:27,450
is, like, definitions.

1264
00:58:27,450 --> 00:58:29,250
And it's never
more in this realm

1265
00:58:29,250 --> 00:58:31,320
that you get the "I don't
know how to define it,

1266
00:58:31,320 --> 00:58:32,820
but I know it when
I see it" sort

1267
00:58:32,820 --> 00:58:35,930
of notion in dealing with terms
for aggression and violence.

1268
00:58:35,930 --> 00:58:38,190
Probably a great
starting point is,

1269
00:58:38,190 --> 00:58:40,860
just as with the
sexual-behavior subject,

1270
00:58:40,860 --> 00:58:43,600
starting off with,
well, what aspects

1271
00:58:43,600 --> 00:58:47,520
of violence and aggression
are unique to humans?

1272
00:58:47,520 --> 00:58:51,210
And what the theme has been
there, for decades now,

1273
00:58:51,210 --> 00:58:54,580
is all sorts of domains that
used to be thought to be

1274
00:58:54,580 --> 00:58:57,400
unique to humans no longer are.

1275
00:58:57,400 --> 00:58:59,220
We've already heard
some of these examples,

1276
00:58:59,220 --> 00:59:01,940
way back in the
sociobiology lectures--

1277
00:59:01,940 --> 00:59:05,230
all of those wildlife films
where, somewhere in there,

1278
00:59:05,230 --> 00:59:09,190
somebody with a very deep voice
has to intone about how "only

1279
00:59:09,190 --> 00:59:13,090
man kills for pleasure"-- while
watching some beasts throwing

1280
00:59:13,090 --> 00:59:14,950
the old wildebeest
into the river, there,

1281
00:59:14,950 --> 00:59:16,290
and misinterpreting it.

1282
00:59:16,290 --> 00:59:18,350
And that was always
the theme-- we're

1283
00:59:18,350 --> 00:59:20,590
the only species that kills.

1284
00:59:20,590 --> 00:59:23,300
And that went down the
tubes, way back when,

1285
00:59:23,300 --> 00:59:27,720
as soon as people started
seeing competitive infanticide.

1286
00:59:27,720 --> 00:59:29,700
That was first seen--
again, I think I

1287
00:59:29,700 --> 00:59:31,760
mentioned-- in langur monkeys.

1288
00:59:31,760 --> 00:59:34,015
A primatologist
named Sara Hrdy, who

1289
00:59:34,015 --> 00:59:35,760
was at Harvard at
the time-- and she

1290
00:59:35,760 --> 00:59:37,230
was the first to report this.

1291
00:59:37,230 --> 00:59:39,440
And-- this could not be!

1292
00:59:39,440 --> 00:59:42,940
That male langur monkeys
were killing babies?

1293
00:59:42,940 --> 00:59:44,010
This was impossible.

1294
00:59:44,010 --> 00:59:48,220
And the interpretation was that
this was a psychopathology.

1295
00:59:48,220 --> 00:59:51,850
This was because of increasing
habitat degradation,

1296
00:59:51,850 --> 00:59:55,480
human populations getting
closer, crowding them in.

1297
00:59:55,480 --> 00:59:58,220
These were populations
of langur monkeys

1298
00:59:58,220 --> 01:00:01,170
in some urban areas in India,
where she was studying them.

1299
01:00:01,170 --> 01:00:05,800
This is not normal, because
no other species kills.

1300
01:00:05,800 --> 01:00:08,350
And now that it's up to
20, 25 different species

1301
01:00:08,350 --> 01:00:11,010
or so that does
competitive infanticide,

1302
01:00:11,010 --> 01:00:14,420
it is quite clear we are not
the only species that kills.

1303
01:00:14,420 --> 01:00:16,070
And we are not the
only species that

1304
01:00:16,070 --> 01:00:21,120
kills in some premeditated,
strategic, Machiavellian,

1305
01:00:21,120 --> 01:00:24,520
good for numbers of copies
of our genes kind of way.

1306
01:00:24,520 --> 01:00:27,770
We are not the only
ones-- Jane Goodall

1307
01:00:27,770 --> 01:00:31,850
by now having documented lots
and lots of cases of murder

1308
01:00:31,850 --> 01:00:35,470
between chimps, females
killing each other's babies,

1309
01:00:35,470 --> 01:00:38,410
males killing other
males quite frequently.

1310
01:00:38,410 --> 01:00:41,630
And, once again, we are
not the only species.

1311
01:00:41,630 --> 01:00:43,980
What's also become clear
from more recent work

1312
01:00:43,980 --> 01:00:46,550
with chimpanzees is,
we're not the only species

1313
01:00:46,550 --> 01:00:48,320
that makes weapons.

1314
01:00:48,320 --> 01:00:52,170
Chimps have now been observed
to take large, heavy branches

1315
01:00:52,170 --> 01:00:55,250
and break off the
ancillary branches,

1316
01:00:55,250 --> 01:00:57,820
there, and smooth it out
and use it as a weapon,

1317
01:00:57,820 --> 01:00:59,750
to try to hit another animal.

1318
01:00:59,750 --> 01:01:03,630
This is tool use
and tool production.

1319
01:01:03,630 --> 01:01:06,500
This is another species
making a weapon.

1320
01:01:06,500 --> 01:01:10,900
We are also not the only species
that has organized violence.

1321
01:01:10,900 --> 01:01:13,200
And this is back,
again, to chimps.

1322
01:01:13,200 --> 01:01:15,490
Something mentioned way
back when in the lectures--

1323
01:01:15,490 --> 01:01:18,740
the facts that chimps
are female-exogamous,

1324
01:01:18,740 --> 01:01:20,650
that business that,
at puberty, it's

1325
01:01:20,650 --> 01:01:23,930
the females who pick up and
move to a different group.

1326
01:01:23,930 --> 01:01:26,910
All of the adult
males in a chimp group

1327
01:01:26,910 --> 01:01:29,700
are relatively
related to each other.

1328
01:01:29,700 --> 01:01:31,230
They are relatives.

1329
01:01:31,230 --> 01:01:35,120
And what you get, then,
is cooperative aggression

1330
01:01:35,120 --> 01:01:37,800
among males from a
particular group.

1331
01:01:37,800 --> 01:01:40,900
What you will see
is border patrols.

1332
01:01:40,900 --> 01:01:44,290
Goodall was the first to use
this term to describe it.

1333
01:01:44,290 --> 01:01:46,000
You will get-- the
males of the group

1334
01:01:46,000 --> 01:01:48,960
will get into an
extremely agitated state

1335
01:01:48,960 --> 01:01:52,680
with each other-- a state
of emotional contagion,

1336
01:01:52,680 --> 01:01:57,940
where they build up this very
high level of excitation.

1337
01:01:57,940 --> 01:02:02,300
And they then go and patrol the
territory between their group

1338
01:02:02,300 --> 01:02:04,130
and the next group over.

1339
01:02:04,130 --> 01:02:06,910
And what Goodall was the
first to document was,

1340
01:02:06,910 --> 01:02:09,500
if they encounter a male
from the other group,

1341
01:02:09,500 --> 01:02:11,160
they will kill him.

1342
01:02:11,160 --> 01:02:16,250
And what she also documented was
cases of groups of male chimps

1343
01:02:16,250 --> 01:02:20,560
systematically killing all of
the males of the neighboring

1344
01:02:20,560 --> 01:02:21,610
group.

1345
01:02:21,610 --> 01:02:24,740
What is it that we've just
seen, now, in another species?

1346
01:02:24,740 --> 01:02:28,970
Genocide-- the notion of killing
an individual not because

1347
01:02:28,970 --> 01:02:33,240
of who they are but because of
what group, what population,

1348
01:02:33,240 --> 01:02:35,670
they belong to, as
part of a desire

1349
01:02:35,670 --> 01:02:38,760
to eradicate a
population as a whole.

1350
01:02:38,760 --> 01:02:41,240
We are not the only
species that has

1351
01:02:41,240 --> 01:02:45,920
something resembling genocide,
if it's termed that way.

1352
01:02:45,920 --> 01:02:49,940
So where is a domain
where we might be unique?

1353
01:02:49,940 --> 01:02:52,450
Lots of people still
argue that humans

1354
01:02:52,450 --> 01:02:55,940
are the only species that
psychopathologically confuse

1355
01:02:55,940 --> 01:02:59,960
sexual behavior with aggressive
behavior-- world of sadism

1356
01:02:59,960 --> 01:03:01,750
and masochism and all of that.

1357
01:03:01,750 --> 01:03:03,930
That appears to be
something resembling

1358
01:03:03,930 --> 01:03:06,920
a human-unique trait.

1359
01:03:06,920 --> 01:03:07,560
OK.

1360
01:03:07,560 --> 01:03:10,460
Now flipping to the more
cheerful side of things--

1361
01:03:10,460 --> 01:03:12,730
the cooperation,
the empathy stuff--

1362
01:03:12,730 --> 01:03:16,760
what aspects of those
behaviors are unique to humans?

1363
01:03:16,760 --> 01:03:18,220
And what people
used to think was

1364
01:03:18,220 --> 01:03:21,096
an exclusively human
ability-- yeah?

1365
01:03:21,096 --> 01:03:25,082
Are there any instances where
certain troops of monkeys

1366
01:03:25,082 --> 01:03:27,526
will not only just kill all
the males in a different troop

1367
01:03:27,526 --> 01:03:29,986
but kill all females
and infants, too,

1368
01:03:29,986 --> 01:03:31,960
as in [INAUDIBLE] genocide?

1369
01:03:31,960 --> 01:03:32,490
Yeah.

1370
01:03:32,490 --> 01:03:35,420
They will kill the infants,
out of competitive infanticide

1371
01:03:35,420 --> 01:03:36,050
stuff.

1372
01:03:36,050 --> 01:03:40,020
And they will then happily
hang with the females.

1373
01:03:40,020 --> 01:03:43,640
And do more than
that, with any luck.

1374
01:03:43,640 --> 01:03:47,290
In terms of-- oh, a very
familiar historical strategy

1375
01:03:47,290 --> 01:03:51,100
with humans, seen
again and again.

1376
01:03:51,100 --> 01:03:52,400
Good end of things.

1377
01:03:52,400 --> 01:03:54,330
Used to be the rule
that the humans were

1378
01:03:54,330 --> 01:03:58,030
the only species that
showed reconciliation-- that

1379
01:03:58,030 --> 01:04:02,270
showed increased likelihood
of affiliative behavior

1380
01:04:02,270 --> 01:04:05,040
between two individuals
after they have

1381
01:04:05,040 --> 01:04:07,520
had an aggressive interaction.

1382
01:04:07,520 --> 01:04:10,390
In the aftermath of
it, increased odds

1383
01:04:10,390 --> 01:04:15,060
of doing something affiliative--
making up-- reconciling.

1384
01:04:15,060 --> 01:04:16,960
Doing something
along those lines.

1385
01:04:16,960 --> 01:04:19,390
And what has emerged
in the last 20 years

1386
01:04:19,390 --> 01:04:24,090
or so is a huge literature
showing reconciliative behavior

1387
01:04:24,090 --> 01:04:26,460
in a couple of
dozen other species.

1388
01:04:26,460 --> 01:04:29,755
First person to report
this-- primatologist Frans de

1389
01:04:29,755 --> 01:04:33,550
Waal, first reporting this
in rhesus monkeys, I believe.

1390
01:04:33,550 --> 01:04:36,930
But lots of other species
since then, including

1391
01:04:36,930 --> 01:04:39,310
dolphins, including whales.

1392
01:04:39,310 --> 01:04:43,750
And what you see is-- in
the aftermath of a fight,

1393
01:04:43,750 --> 01:04:47,840
you see two individuals are
more likely-- in gorillas,

1394
01:04:47,840 --> 01:04:51,170
for example, to do social
grooming in the aftermath--

1395
01:04:51,170 --> 01:04:52,560
than at any other time.

1396
01:04:52,560 --> 01:04:56,930
An increased rate of that
happening-- reconciliation.

1397
01:04:56,930 --> 01:05:00,620
What's remarkable is some
of the subtleties in it.

1398
01:05:00,620 --> 01:05:04,340
And this was work that was done
by Marina Cords, at Columbia.

1399
01:05:04,340 --> 01:05:08,320
And what she showed was,
the odds of reconciliation

1400
01:05:08,320 --> 01:05:10,910
increase when it's
a more important,

1401
01:05:10,910 --> 01:05:14,050
valuable relationship
that you have.

1402
01:05:14,050 --> 01:05:16,610
How was she showing this?

1403
01:05:16,610 --> 01:05:19,410
These were studies
with macaque monkeys.

1404
01:05:19,410 --> 01:05:21,700
And what she did was
set up circumstances--

1405
01:05:21,700 --> 01:05:24,970
these were animals
that were caged.

1406
01:05:24,970 --> 01:05:27,180
And there were
circumstances where

1407
01:05:27,180 --> 01:05:31,520
she put food on a tray outside
that could be reached for.

1408
01:05:31,520 --> 01:05:33,900
Where, in one setting,
an animal could

1409
01:05:33,900 --> 01:05:36,080
get the food in all on its own.

1410
01:05:36,080 --> 01:05:37,790
And in another
setting, the only way

1411
01:05:37,790 --> 01:05:40,570
to get the food tray
close enough to the cage

1412
01:05:40,570 --> 01:05:42,640
was if both of them cooperated.

1413
01:05:42,640 --> 01:05:44,890
And this was what they
were doing habitually.

1414
01:05:44,890 --> 01:05:46,480
So what's the difference, there?

1415
01:05:46,480 --> 01:05:48,420
In the second case,
you have formed

1416
01:05:48,420 --> 01:05:51,780
this cooperative relationship
with this other individual.

1417
01:05:51,780 --> 01:05:54,280
You need them, and they
need you to pull off

1418
01:05:54,280 --> 01:05:56,590
this getting the food
close to the cage business.

1419
01:05:56,590 --> 01:05:59,520
What she showed was
significantly higher rates

1420
01:05:59,520 --> 01:06:01,950
of reconciliation
between pairs that

1421
01:06:01,950 --> 01:06:04,440
have a history of cooperating.

1422
01:06:04,440 --> 01:06:06,530
What could that
be interpreted as?

1423
01:06:06,530 --> 01:06:09,840
More of a game-theory
history of cooperation

1424
01:06:09,840 --> 01:06:12,210
behind you-- more
willingness to forgive.

1425
01:06:12,210 --> 01:06:14,770
Another way of framing it,
as she does in her work,

1426
01:06:14,770 --> 01:06:17,830
is, this is a more valuable
relationship that you

1427
01:06:17,830 --> 01:06:19,260
don't want to screw up.

1428
01:06:19,260 --> 01:06:22,540
You are more willing to do
something reconciliative

1429
01:06:22,540 --> 01:06:24,200
afterward.

1430
01:06:24,200 --> 01:06:28,330
You can see, in baboons,
reconciling behavior

1431
01:06:28,330 --> 01:06:29,710
in females.

1432
01:06:29,710 --> 01:06:32,370
No male baboons ever reconcile.

1433
01:06:32,370 --> 01:06:34,690
Showing gender
differences, there.

1434
01:06:34,690 --> 01:06:37,840
In bonobos, you
see reconciliation

1435
01:06:37,840 --> 01:06:40,090
is different from all
these other species, where,

1436
01:06:40,090 --> 01:06:43,314
in all the other ones, it's
built around social grooming

1437
01:06:43,314 --> 01:06:45,770
or chimp hugs or whatever.

1438
01:06:45,770 --> 01:06:48,710
There, of course, as you
guessed it, it's sex.

1439
01:06:48,710 --> 01:06:50,230
Because with the
bonobos, anything

1440
01:06:50,230 --> 01:06:52,860
that happens, and
it's time to have sex.

1441
01:06:52,860 --> 01:06:54,730
But an interesting
thing, in terms

1442
01:06:54,730 --> 01:06:58,940
of this picture of bonobos
being this incredibly peaceful

1443
01:06:58,940 --> 01:07:02,810
species out there in this
commune and all of that--

1444
01:07:02,810 --> 01:07:06,840
you can't have reconciliation
unless you have aggression.

1445
01:07:06,840 --> 01:07:08,600
They do have aggressive
interactions.

1446
01:07:08,600 --> 01:07:11,680
Otherwise, there would be
nothing to reconcile afterward.

1447
01:07:11,680 --> 01:07:15,900
Even the beatific bonobos have
a certain degree of aggression--

1448
01:07:15,900 --> 01:07:19,640
very high and varied
rates, varied abilities,

1449
01:07:19,640 --> 01:07:23,340
to pull off reconciliative
behavior afterward.

1450
01:07:23,340 --> 01:07:25,900
More things that used
to be just about us.

1451
01:07:25,900 --> 01:07:27,030
Empathy.

1452
01:07:27,030 --> 01:07:30,180
And a literature now coming
out, showing the building

1453
01:07:30,180 --> 01:07:33,050
blocks of that in
other species, as well.

1454
01:07:33,050 --> 01:07:38,670
First example in chimps,
second example in lab rats.

1455
01:07:38,670 --> 01:07:39,550
Chimp example.

1456
01:07:39,550 --> 01:07:42,280
Again, this was work
done by Frans de Waal.

1457
01:07:42,280 --> 01:07:43,760
And wonderful study.

1458
01:07:43,760 --> 01:07:46,270
What he showed were
two circumstances

1459
01:07:46,270 --> 01:07:48,430
where a male chimp
would get pummeled.

1460
01:07:48,430 --> 01:07:50,000
First circumstance.

1461
01:07:50,000 --> 01:07:54,340
You've got this low-ranking
male who goes up and threatens

1462
01:07:54,340 --> 01:07:56,550
and starts a fight with
a higher-ranking male

1463
01:07:56,550 --> 01:07:59,330
and gets pummeled
into the ground.

1464
01:07:59,330 --> 01:08:00,700
Second circumstance.

1465
01:08:00,700 --> 01:08:02,100
Low-ranking guy
is sitting there,

1466
01:08:02,100 --> 01:08:03,310
minding his own business.

1467
01:08:03,310 --> 01:08:05,260
High-ranking guy
is in a bad mood

1468
01:08:05,260 --> 01:08:07,430
and pummels him into the ground.

1469
01:08:07,430 --> 01:08:08,680
What's the difference?

1470
01:08:08,680 --> 01:08:11,760
In the first case,
this kid started it,

1471
01:08:11,760 --> 01:08:12,985
by challenging the guy.

1472
01:08:12,985 --> 01:08:16,750
And in the second case, he
was an innocent bystander.

1473
01:08:16,750 --> 01:08:19,490
And what de Waal showed
is, in the half hour

1474
01:08:19,490 --> 01:08:23,310
after these incidents, the ones
who were innocent bystanders

1475
01:08:23,310 --> 01:08:27,300
were far more likely to be
groomed by females there

1476
01:08:27,300 --> 01:08:29,770
in the group than the
ones who had started it.

1477
01:08:29,770 --> 01:08:33,550
They were able to distinguish
between not just that this

1478
01:08:33,550 --> 01:08:35,810
is an individual
